														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2388880">
									

<p>In my opinion the 'supposedly' that you're referring to is pretty much when it's used sarcastically. I think it would be fair to assume that in a clinical, scientific article people would not be using sarcasm and would be using 'supposedly' properly.</p>
<p>&quot;accepted or believed as true, without positive knowledge&quot; seems like a fitting definition.</p>
<p>e: However, I agree that &quot;it is currently thought that&quot; or something similar fits in more with The Foundation's non-presumptive nature.</p>

							</div>

								
